/*
Problem Statement:: Given two binary strings a and b, return their sum as a binary string.
Example 1:
Input: a = "11", b = "1"
Output: "100"
Example 2:
Input: a = "1010", b = "1011"
Output: "10101"
 
Constraints:
1 <= a.length, b.length <= 104
a and b consist only of '0' or '1' characters.
Each string does not contain leading zeros except for the zero itself.

*/
class Solution {
    public String addBinary(String a, String b) 
    {
       StringBuilder st=new StringBuilder();
       int carry=0;
       int n1=a.length();
       int n2=b.length();
       int i=n1-1;
       int j=n2-1;
       while(i>=0 || j>=0)
       {
         int sum=carry+(i>=0 ?a.charAt(i)-'0' : 0)+(j>=0 ?b.charAt(j)-'0':0);
         st.append((sum%2)==0 ? 0 :1);
         i--;
         j--;
         carry=sum/2;
       }
       if(carry!=0)
       {
        st.append(carry);
       }
       return st.reverse().toString();
    }
}
//TC:O(N)
//SC:O(1)
/*
Approach: Simple do Binary Addition, don't convert into Binary String or vice verse due to protect from overflowing,
once add from right index and then proceed to the left index if sum>1 then carry=1 or else carry will be 0, compute sum as carry(incase carry>0)+string1 char value and str2 car value (simple addition),sum%2 will give you the right index value(vaue to store) if the sum is >single digit


*/
